Today, it's nearly impossible
to get a good job in America

01:07.867 --> 01:09.027
without a college degree.

01:09.069 --> 01:11.036
But with tuition costs soaring,

01:11.138 --> 01:14.705
70% of all college students
are taking out loans,

01:14.808 --> 01:18.043
and many are finding it
impossible to get out of debt

01:18.145 --> 01:19.244
once they graduate.

01:19.346 --> 01:21.546
And that could have
a long-term socioeconomic

01:21.648 --> 01:24.615
impact on America
for generations to come.

01:31.191 --> 01:33.758
We're at High Point
University in North Carolina,

01:33.860 --> 01:35.360
and we're here to go
on a campus tour.

02:06.659 --> 02:08.293
Toboni:
<i>High Point University</i>

02:08.395 --> 02:11.863
<i>is pumping more than $2 billion
into campus improvements.</i>

02:11.965 --> 02:14.732
<i>There are seven pools,
jacuzzis, beach volleyball,</i>

02:14.834 --> 02:19.004
<i>concierge service, valet,
an arcade, a cinema,</i>

02:19.106 --> 02:21.506
<i>and a first-class
airplane lounge.</i>

02:21.608 --> 02:25.043
As our tour guide told us,
you can sit here and study

02:25.145 --> 02:27.025
so can get used
to the real world,

02:27.047 --> 02:29.780
where you're gonna have to fly
for your business meetings.

02:31.951 --> 02:34.419
<i>But perks like these come
at a steep cost.</i>

02:34.521 --> 02:37.755
<i>High Point has increased
its tuition by nearly 70%</i>

02:37.857 --> 02:39.124
<i>over the last decade.</i>

02:39.226 --> 02:41.467
<i>Luxurious amenities help
attract more students,</i>

02:41.528 --> 02:44.095
<i>which means more tuition
checks for the college.</i>

02:44.197 --> 02:46.097
<i>Over the last 20 years,</i>

02:46.199 --> 02:47.698
<i>tuition at American universities</i>

02:47.800 --> 02:50.101
<i>has skyrocketed,
and as a result,</i>

02:50.203 --> 02:53.038
<i>debt per student has doubled.</i>

02:53.140 --> 02:55.940
<i>It's crippling borrowers
like Chaitra McCarty,</i>

02:56.043 --> 02:58.843
<i>who attended Wheelock College.</i>

02:58.945 --> 03:02.180
Ever since I was little, I knew
I wanted to work with kids.

03:02.282 --> 03:04.049
So, when I decided on Wheelock,

03:04.151 --> 03:06.351
<i>I knew that they had
a great reputation.</i>

03:06.453 --> 03:10.255
And that school seemed like it
was the perfect fit for me.

03:10.357 --> 03:12.590
And was it sort of like, "We'll
worry about the money later"?

03:12.692 --> 03:14.526
Yeah, absolutely. Yeah.

03:14.627 --> 03:17.095
Bianca, you did an amazing job.

03:17.197 --> 03:19.464
Toboni: How much do
you owe right now?

03:19.566 --> 03:21.966
I owe $158,000.

03:22.069 --> 03:25.170
A month I pay 850
for my private loans

03:25.272 --> 03:27.872
and then the federal
loans, I pay 472.

03:27.974 --> 03:30.408
So, about half
of your monthly income

03:30.510 --> 03:32.310
- is going to you paying off your student debt.
- Right.

03:32.412 --> 03:34.932
How does it make you feel when
you, when you think about that?

03:34.981 --> 03:36.247
Hopeless!

03:36.349 --> 03:37.949
Will you be able
to pay that back?

03:38.051 --> 03:39.551
I mean, we don't have a choice.

03:40.720 --> 03:41.960
Toboni:
<i>Compounding the problem</i>

03:42.021 --> 03:43.354
<i>is that Chaitra and her husband</i>

03:43.457 --> 03:46.558
<i>both needed Master's degrees
to continue teaching.</i>

03:46.659 --> 03:48.299
<i>With all those loans to pay off,</i>

03:48.395 --> 03:50.795
<i>they're stuck living
with Chaitra's mom.</i>

03:50.897 --> 03:55.866
You guys together have
around $290,000 in loans.

03:55.969 --> 03:58.103
Yeah, it's... it's crazy.

03:58.205 --> 04:00.305
That... that's a
whole house.

04:00.407 --> 04:03.374
You know, that's a... that's a
really decent house. Yeah.

04:03.477 --> 04:06.010
But we own that in loans, so.

04:06.113 --> 04:07.678
Chaitra:
By 30, I think I just...

04:07.780 --> 04:10.515
I saw myself married with
a house and with kids.

04:10.617 --> 04:11.949
You have this student debt

04:12.051 --> 04:14.119
and you can't hit milestones

04:14.221 --> 04:16.553
like buying a house
or even just living

04:16.656 --> 04:18.755
in a place that's yours,
having children.

04:18.858 --> 04:20.137
It's definitely
really difficult.

04:20.192 --> 04:23.027
I mean, you can't file for
bankruptcy on student loans.

04:23.130 --> 04:26.897
The system is not conducive
to help individuals like us.

04:27.000 --> 04:29.834
Toboni: <i>Under US law, you
can file for bankruptcy</i>

04:29.936 --> 04:32.504
<i>to free yourself from
almost any kind of debt,</i>

04:32.606 --> 04:34.572
<i>but not from student loans.</i>

04:34.674 --> 04:37.542
<i>So, those debts stay
on the books forever.</i>

04:37.644 --> 04:40.478
Right now we've got
about $1.2 trillion

04:40.580 --> 04:44.549
in outstanding student loans owed
by about 42 million Americans.

04:44.651 --> 04:47.485
<i>Ben Miller specializes in
higher education policy</i>

04:47.587 --> 04:49.754
<i>at the Center for
American Progress.</i>

04:49.856 --> 04:52.290
The student loan problem is
ultimately a tuition problem.

04:52.392 --> 04:54.792
Because states are spending
less and less money

04:54.894 --> 04:57.529
on higher education,
tuition keeps rising.

04:57.631 --> 04:59.197
Family income stays stagnant

04:59.299 --> 05:01.999
and people have to borrow
to make up the difference.

05:02.101 --> 05:03.868
What that means is
we've directly shifted

05:03.970 --> 05:06.371
the cost of college
away from states

05:06.473 --> 05:07.672
onto the backs of students.

05:07.774 --> 05:09.507
Toboni:
<i>To help students pay,</i>

05:09.609 --> 05:11.309
<i>the US government issues loans</i>

05:11.411 --> 05:13.878
<i>to every single applicant,
good for tuition</i>

05:13.980 --> 05:15.613
<i>at any accredited school.</i>

05:15.715 --> 05:17.815
<i>But 43% of the borrowing</i>

05:17.917 --> 05:20.185
<i>is to pay for tuition
at public schools,</i>

05:20.287 --> 05:21.687
<i>which are supposed to
be affordable,</i>

05:21.754 --> 05:23.988
<i>but which have been raising
their tuition rates</i>

05:24.090 --> 05:27.559
<i>to make up for dwindling
state spending.</i>

05:27.661 --> 05:30.228
<i>Louisiana has cut more
funding to its state schools</i>

05:30.330 --> 05:32.330
<i>than any other state
in the country.</i>

05:32.432 --> 05:34.765
<i>So, we spoke with
the president of LSU</i>

05:34.867 --> 05:38.203
<i>about how these cuts
affect higher education.</i>

05:38.305 --> 05:40.771
We've been dis-investing
in higher Ed.

05:40.873 --> 05:42.440
At a very, very rapid rate.

05:42.542 --> 05:44.609
I'd say in '08, we were 70/30.

05:44.711 --> 05:47.478
70% state, 30% student.

05:47.581 --> 05:49.180
We're 80/20 right now.

05:49.282 --> 05:51.583
80% student, 20% state.

05:51.685 --> 05:53.484
When you lose
that much state funding,

05:53.587 --> 05:55.253
I mean, how much
has tuition gone up?

05:55.355 --> 05:57.154
Tuition has
gone up significantly.

05:57.257 --> 05:58.423
About 65% for us.

05:58.525 --> 06:01.526
We're quietly privatizing
public higher education.

06:01.628 --> 06:02.694
Throughout the country.

06:02.795 --> 06:03.894
The children
in elementary school

06:03.996 --> 06:06.197
are not gonna have a
public, affordable option

06:06.299 --> 06:07.965
by the time they get
out of high school.

06:08.067 --> 06:09.133
Toboni:
<i>To find out why</i>

06:09.236 --> 06:11.316
<i>Louisiana is cutting
more and more funding</i>

06:11.338 --> 06:12.537
<i>from its public universities,</i>

06:12.639 --> 06:14.939
<i>we spoke with Governor
John Bel Edwards,</i>

06:15.041 --> 06:18.509
<i>who is dealing with the budget
deficit of $600 million.</i>

06:18.612 --> 06:20.345
Toboni: While campaigning
for this position,

06:20.447 --> 06:22.913
- you talked about investing more in higher education.
- Yes.

06:23.015 --> 06:24.782
It's obviously something
that's important to you.

06:24.884 --> 06:28.119
Um, and still you're proposing
budget cuts for schools like LSU

06:28.221 --> 06:29.501
that need the state funding.

06:29.522 --> 06:31.322
'Cause I have a
constitutional obligation

06:31.424 --> 06:32.545
to deliver a balanced budget,

06:32.559 --> 06:34.525
and the cuts have to
come from somewhere.

06:34.628 --> 06:37.629
So, the cuts are coming at the
expense of higher education

06:37.731 --> 06:39.497
and also the expense of students

06:39.599 --> 06:41.566
in order to keep those
universities afloat.

06:41.668 --> 06:45.570
Students have access to
money, so do lawmakers think,

06:45.672 --> 06:47.772
"Well, we won't put
money towards this

06:47.874 --> 06:49.540
"'cause we know that
students can take out debt

06:49.643 --> 06:51.123
and pay for their
education that way"?

06:51.177 --> 06:54.912
Well, obviously that is
happening to some degree

06:55.014 --> 06:57.214
not just in Louisiana,
but around the country,

06:57.317 --> 06:59.784
and I find it very troubling.

06:59.886 --> 07:01.586
Toboni: <i>While public schools
are increasingly reliant</i>

07:01.688 --> 07:04.155
<i>on student loans just
to cover their costs,</i>

07:04.257 --> 07:06.891
<i>for-profit colleges
are run as businesses,</i>

07:06.993 --> 07:08.893
<i>and many people believe
they intentionally</i>

07:08.995 --> 07:12.062
<i>take advantage
of the loan system.</i>

07:12.165 --> 07:14.965
While only about 10% of
students who go to college

07:15.067 --> 07:16.467
in the US go
to for-profits,

07:16.569 --> 07:18.469
but nearly 40% of students

07:18.571 --> 07:21.105
who default on student
loans go to these schools.

07:21.207 --> 07:23.274
<i>We met with Maggie Scheel,</i>

07:23.376 --> 07:25.042
<i>who is struggling
to make ends meet</i>

07:25.144 --> 07:28.313
<i>after taking out loans to
attend a for-profit school.</i>

07:30.049 --> 07:31.289
<i>Maggie graduated with honors</i>

07:31.384 --> 07:33.651
<i>from a four-year program
in criminal justice</i>

07:33.753 --> 07:36.621
<i>at Globe University Minnesota's
School of Business.</i>

07:36.723 --> 07:38.623
At the time, I was ecstatic

07:38.725 --> 07:40.692
and they sold me on this dream.

07:40.794 --> 07:44.829
You know, and it just turned
out to be a nightmare.

07:46.800 --> 07:48.361
Maggie: I missed a lot
of time with Jon,

07:48.435 --> 07:50.401
you know, being a single parent,

07:50.503 --> 07:51.902
to think that we were
gonna get somewhere,

07:52.004 --> 07:53.671
and so to end up here,

07:53.773 --> 07:54.839
it's sad.

07:54.941 --> 07:56.741
Toboni: <i>Maggie said
that admission officers</i>

07:56.843 --> 07:58.142
<i>urged her to take out loans</i>

07:58.244 --> 08:00.077
<i>and that they gave her
unreliable information</i>

08:00.179 --> 08:02.112
<i>about the value of the
degree she'd be getting.</i>

08:02.215 --> 08:05.215
What did the director of admissions
tell you in that first meeting?

08:05.251 --> 08:06.851
I wanted to do probation.

08:06.953 --> 08:08.419
He really pushed that

08:08.521 --> 08:11.188
they had almost 100% placement
in criminal justice.

08:11.290 --> 08:14.258
So you were pretty much
guaranteed that you would get

08:14.361 --> 08:16.894
- job placement once you graduated.
- Right.

08:16.996 --> 08:19.330
Toboni: <i>Despite having
a four-year degree</i>

08:19.432 --> 08:20.931
<i>and good grades, the only job</i>

08:21.033 --> 08:22.299
<i>that she's been able to get</i>

08:22.402 --> 08:25.269
<i>doesn't require
a college degree at all.</i>

08:25.372 --> 08:27.972
I owe just over 38 now.
38,000.

08:28.074 --> 08:30.908
Last month I made $650.

08:31.010 --> 08:33.644
Can I ask how much money you have
in your bank account right now?

08:33.746 --> 08:34.746
16 cents.

08:34.780 --> 08:36.260
- Right now 16 cents?
- Yep.

08:36.315 --> 08:39.183
And we're about two months
behind on all of our bills.

08:39.284 --> 08:41.519
But, so, like, literally,
how do you pay your loans?

08:41.621 --> 08:43.688
I don't.
I'm defaulted right now.

08:43.789 --> 08:46.391
They took my taxes this year.

08:46.493 --> 08:48.893
It's just a constant struggle.

08:53.767 --> 08:54.699
<i>Maggie is now working</i>

08:54.801 --> 08:56.300
<i>with the state attorney general,</i>

08:56.403 --> 08:58.536
<i>who is suing the school for
misleading potential students.</i>

08:58.638 --> 09:00.605
<i>We sat down with the two of them</i>

09:00.707 --> 09:04.108
<i>and Jason Jensen, a former
Globe admissions officer.</i>

09:04.210 --> 09:06.730
What they're doing with people
is using the job placement rate

09:06.813 --> 09:08.933
to make the school sound
like it's a sure bet.

09:08.981 --> 09:10.548
With regards to
business administration,

09:10.650 --> 09:13.818
we had the school counting
people as being placed,

09:13.920 --> 09:16.687
even though maybe they
were working as a barista

09:16.790 --> 09:18.289
at Starbucks,
which is a business.

09:18.391 --> 09:22.393
Did you feel like you had to exaggerate
the benefits of this education?

09:22.495 --> 09:23.628
Oh yeah.

09:23.730 --> 09:26.898
My goal was to find the
prospective student's pain.

09:26.999 --> 09:30.067
So, if you were a single mother
with two or three kids at home,

09:30.169 --> 09:32.569
are you making enough money
to provide for your family?

09:32.572 --> 09:33.905
Furthering your education,

09:34.006 --> 09:36.006
doesn't that sound like
a great option for you?

09:36.108 --> 09:38.943
Toboni: <i>Globe University didn't
respond to our request for comment,</i>

09:39.045 --> 09:41.178
<i>but they deny the attorney
general's allegations,</i>

09:41.280 --> 09:43.915
<i>and have previously said that
they are "fully compliant"</i>

09:44.016 --> 09:45.316
<i>with Minnesota law and that</i>

09:45.418 --> 09:46.658
<i>the placement numbers they share</i>

09:46.686 --> 09:49.119
<i>with prospective student
are regularly reported</i>

09:49.221 --> 09:52.222
<i>to the accrediting body
that oversees the school.</i>

09:52.325 --> 09:54.725
The problem here is
this is students' lives

09:54.828 --> 09:55.760
and it's their futures.

09:55.862 --> 09:57.728
They're saddled
with student loans

09:57.831 --> 09:59.992
that can't be discharged
in bankruptcy.

10:00.032 --> 10:02.533
They are going to be
with them for... forever.

10:02.635 --> 10:04.401
If the student
ends up defaulting,

10:04.504 --> 10:07.004
then the American taxpayers
pick up the tab for that.

10:07.106 --> 10:11.476
Taxpayers lose, the students
lose, but the school gets paid.

10:11.578 --> 10:13.538
Toboni: <i>Under our
student loan system,</i>

10:13.613 --> 10:14.979
<i>the government is the lender.</i>

10:15.081 --> 10:16.313
<i>So, when students default,</i>

10:16.415 --> 10:18.495
<i>it's the taxpayers
who are on the hook.</i>

10:18.518 --> 10:21.886
<i>And the schools they attended
get to keep he money.</i>

10:21.988 --> 10:23.588
The federal government
tends to take the approach

10:23.690 --> 10:25.931
of assuming all these colleges
are doing the right thing,

10:26.025 --> 10:27.905
when what we see
repeatedly is they don't.

10:27.994 --> 10:31.195
Miller: Almost every major
for-profit college has been

10:31.297 --> 10:32.930
under some sort
of investigation.

10:33.032 --> 10:36.066
And it's still getting several
billion dollars a year

10:36.168 --> 10:37.301
from the US taxpayers.

10:37.403 --> 10:38.903
You know, it's almost
like the same situation

10:39.005 --> 10:40.337
we saw with the banks
around the recession

10:40.439 --> 10:44.074
where no one was really held
for account for what they did.

10:44.176 --> 10:45.510
And the same thing
is happening here.

10:45.612 --> 10:48.178
Toboni: <i>The astronomical
levels of debt and default</i>

10:48.280 --> 10:50.347
<i>are getting the attention
of a growing number</i>

10:50.449 --> 10:52.282
<i>of federal lawmakers.</i>

10:52.385 --> 10:54.919
This is truly
an economic emergency.

10:55.021 --> 10:57.421
<i>Elizabeth Warren
is leading the fight</i>

10:57.524 --> 10:59.824
<i>to change the way we
finance higher education.</i>

10:59.926 --> 11:01.492
So we now live in an America

11:01.594 --> 11:06.063
where an education is necessary
to push this economy forward,

11:06.165 --> 11:07.532
to push this country forward,

11:07.634 --> 11:11.035
and yet the debt to pay
for that education,

11:11.137 --> 11:12.417
it's holding us back.

11:12.438 --> 11:14.639
How will this affect
the economy long-term?

11:14.741 --> 11:15.673
Young people

11:15.775 --> 11:18.108
are not moving out
of their parents' homes

11:18.210 --> 11:19.644
at the ages we would expect.

11:19.746 --> 11:22.780
They're not buying cars,
they're not buying homes,

11:22.882 --> 11:24.982
they're not starting
small businesses.

11:25.084 --> 11:28.853
We have never had a moment
like this before in America.

11:28.955 --> 11:30.588
Toboni: <i>The problem
isn't just that</i>

11:30.690 --> 11:31.850
<i>students are getting into debt</i>

11:31.858 --> 11:34.025
<i>at record levels,
it's that the quality</i>

11:34.126 --> 11:37.294
<i>of the education they're
paying for is slipping, too.</i>

11:37.396 --> 11:40.998
On average, do we as Americans
get the best education

11:41.100 --> 11:43.267
- compared to other developed countries?
- We don't.

11:43.369 --> 11:44.902
Miller: Our most
prestigious schools,

11:45.004 --> 11:47.237
that are the best in the
world, mask a lot of problems

11:47.339 --> 11:48.900
that are going on
for the broad base set

11:48.942 --> 11:50.174
of the Americans
that go to college.

11:50.276 --> 11:52.509
We spend about $23,000 a year

11:52.612 --> 11:54.178
per person on higher education.

11:54.280 --> 11:56.814
The international average
is about $10,000.

11:56.916 --> 11:59.677
So, we're spending a lot more
money than most other countries.

11:59.719 --> 12:01.351
Toboni:
<i>Two decades ago,</i>

12:01.454 --> 12:03.454
<i>the US was first
in graduation rates</i>

12:03.556 --> 12:05.656
<i>compared to other
developed countries.</i>

12:05.758 --> 12:07.692
<i>Today, we're 15th.</i>

12:07.794 --> 12:10.094
<i>And across several
core indicators,</i>

12:10.196 --> 12:11.729
<i>we're losing ground
in the quality</i>

12:11.831 --> 12:13.397
<i>of our higher education.</i>

12:13.499 --> 12:15.265
So, we're spending more
on education

12:15.367 --> 12:16.647
than any other
developed country.

12:16.703 --> 12:19.436
We're putting millions
of students in debt,

12:19.538 --> 12:22.473
and we're still not
competing internationally

12:22.575 --> 12:24.508
- the way we were in the past.
- That's correct.

12:24.611 --> 12:26.844
That's a lot of money to spend
to just get mediocrity.

12:26.946 --> 12:30.681
Toboni: <i>But even as our students
fall behind other countries,</i>

12:30.783 --> 12:34.384
<i>one state is fundamentally
changing the system.</i>

12:34.487 --> 12:36.988
<i>Republican Governor
Bill Haslam of Tennessee</i>

12:37.090 --> 12:40.424
<i>started an innovative program
called Tennessee Promise.</i>

12:40.526 --> 12:43.260
<i>The program allows
any high school graduate</i>

12:43.362 --> 12:45.562
<i>to attend an in-state
community college</i>

12:45.665 --> 12:47.632
<i>debt free for two years.</i>

