We've been doing a thing
on fecal transplants.

19:05.478 --> 19:08.879
I was curious, uh, how
long was the idea around?

19:22.028 --> 19:24.461
We had a friend
who was a veterinarian

19:24.563 --> 19:28.165
and he told Johannes
about the fact

19:28.267 --> 19:33.003
that veterinarians had been
treating diarrhea in horses

19:33.105 --> 19:35.972
with stool from healthy horses

19:36.075 --> 19:38.308
for a long time.
For probably 400 years.

19:38.411 --> 19:41.245
Was it ever, like, a hard sell

19:41.347 --> 19:42.879
on people in
the medical community

19:42.981 --> 19:45.982
to undergo, uh,
such a novel treatment?

19:46.085 --> 19:48.718
Yeah, you... you took a lot of
flack from your colleagues.

19:48.820 --> 19:51.621
Yeah. But then
within six months,

19:51.723 --> 19:55.192
they called him up and wanted
to know what his protocol was.

19:55.294 --> 19:56.726
So, it must have...

19:56.828 --> 19:59.796
- you know, it stirred some interest.
- Yeah.

19:59.898 --> 20:02.299
Morton: <i>Since the medical
establishment has come around</i>

20:02.401 --> 20:04.101
<i>on the procedure,
it's been performed</i>

20:04.203 --> 20:05.269
<i>thousands of times</i>

20:05.371 --> 20:07.131
<i>at hospitals and clinics
across the country.</i>

20:07.173 --> 20:08.774
<i>So much so that it's led
to the creation</i>

20:08.874 --> 20:10.474
<i>of the first
independent stool bank</i>

20:10.576 --> 20:13.210
<i>called OpenBiome
right outside of Boston.</i>

